		<title>Watch A Video of Your Visitors – DeskTime</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/WeeklyWebTools/~3/nGLNmkXn0mk/watch-a-video-of-your-visitors-desktime</link>
		<comments>http://weeklywebtools.com/podcast/watch-a-video-of-your-visitors-desktime#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 19 Mar 2012 00:00:22 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>jammindave@gmail.com (David Jackson)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Podcast]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://weeklywebtools.com/?p=976</guid>
		<description>I just found out a great WordPress plugin that records video of your visitors when they are on your site. Want to know why people aren&amp;#8217;t signing up for that newsletter? Want to know why they are not subscribing to that podcast? Ordering that product? Say goodbye to analytics, and say hello to&amp;#8230;..well,,, spying pretty [...]</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><p>I just found out a great WordPress plugin that records video of your visitors when they are on your site. Want to know why people aren&#8217;t signing up for that newsletter? Want to know why they are not subscribing to that podcast? Ordering that product? Say goodbye to analytics, and say hello to&#8230;..well,,, spying pretty much. This plugin records video of their visit and takes all the guesswork out. Then you can run reports on their activities. It also allows you to create campaigns to track converstions. It&#8217;s really impressive. When I went to their website, I was sure this was going to be a plugin that had a monthly fee, or <em>something</em> to handle to stress of all these video recordings.</p>
<p>What I found was amazing. The pricing for a single wesbite is $47. If you want it on three websites, it&#8217;s only $10 more. If you want it on unlmiited websites, it&#8217;s only $97 which is nothing compared to the insights you will get from this pulgin. This also includes lifetime upgrades. If you&#8217;re looking for a catch, let me know if you find one as I sure can&#8217;t find it. For more information go to <a title="First Time Visitor" href="http://www.firsttimevisitor.com" target="_blank">www.firsttimevisitor.com</a></p>
<p>Watch the video<br />
<object width="450" height="259" classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0"><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><param name="src" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/WLkQCbkfu3M?version=3&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0" /><param name="allowfullscreen" value="true" /><embed width="450" height="259" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/WLkQCbkfu3M?version=3&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0" allowFullScreen="true" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" /></object></p>
<h3>Live Statistics Show Who is Slacking at Work</h3>
<p>If you want to track your own productivity, or see live stats of your employees desktime.com will help you. It&#8217;s a great tool that not only works on Mac, PC, but it also works with iPhones and Android devices. When users install DeskTime on their computers, it tracks what kind of applications the person is using and is analyzing it against a modifiable database of productive, distracting and neutral applications. For time tracking DeskTime detects mouse and other input devices. On DeskTime you can group employees into groups like &#8220;Marketing&#8221;, &#8220;Sales&#8221;, &#8220;Management&#8221; etc. Group allows you to define what applications are productive, unproductive or neutral for each group. For example, Facebook and Twitter is a productive application for social media managers while it is unproductive for others. You can set these values by hovering the necessary app in employee view. Additionaly, you can select what groups you want to see in the Dashboard view. It&#8217;s only $9 a month per employee and the boost in productivity could be well worth it. Check it out at <a title="Desktime Time Tracking Tools" href="http://desktime.com" target="_blank">desktime.com</a></p>
